{"session_id":"svc-1778063894901996656","seq":0,"type":"session.start","ts":"2026-05-06T10:38:19.009838827Z","data":{"provider":"","model":"gpt-5.4-mini","resolved_harness":"codex","harness_source":"auto_route","resolved_model":"gpt-5.4-mini","work_dir":"/tmp/ddx-exec-wt/.execute-bead-wt-ddx-317d0254-20260506T103812-a69e960f","max_iterations":0,"prompt":"\u003cexecute-bead\u003e\n  \u003cinstructions\u003e\nYou are executing one bead inside an isolated DDx execution worktree. The bead\u0026#39;s \u0026lt;description\u0026gt; and \u0026lt;acceptance\u0026gt; are the completion contract — every AC must be provably satisfied by a specific code, test, or file you can point to after your commit.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Step 0: size check\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;The bead is too big when any of these holds:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- More than ~6 ACs spanning unrelated subsystems.\u0026#xA;- AC mixes design, implementation, integration tests, and docs as separate top-level deliverables.\u0026#xA;- Description names multiple feature-sized sub-pieces.\u0026#xA;- More than ~500 lines across more than ~5 files in unrelated packages.\u0026#xA;- If the bead description exceeds 8000 bytes, treat Step 0 as a split-first pass and favor child-bead scoping before implementation.\u0026#xA;- Auto-decomposition is capped at depth 2: root beads may split once, decomposed children may split once more, and third-level splits must be rejected with an explanation.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;If too big, decompose — do not attempt the work:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;1. `ddx bead create` for each child slice (focused title, description, AC; copy parent\u0026#39;s labels and spec-id).\u0026#xA;2. `ddx bead dep add \u0026lt;child-id\u0026gt; \u0026lt;parent-id\u0026gt;` to record edges.\u0026#xA;3. `ddx bead update \u0026lt;parent-id\u0026gt; --notes \u0026#39;decomposed into \u0026lt;child-ids\u0026gt;\u0026#39;` so the decomposition is visible.\u0026#xA;4. Write `.ddx/executions/20260506T103812-a69e960f/no_changes_rationale.txt` listing each child ID and slice, then stop.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;A clean decomposition is a successful attempt. Do not mix partial implementation with decomposition.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## How to work\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- Read first. If the bead names files, specs, or prior beads, read them before editing — do not guess.\u0026#xA;- Cross-reference each AC against concrete evidence (test name, file path, function) before committing. If you cannot point at it, it is not done.\u0026#xA;- Run the project\u0026#39;s test and lint commands before committing. **Do not commit red code** — fix failures first.\u0026#xA;- Stage with `git add \u0026lt;specific-paths\u0026gt;`; never `git add -A` (the worktree may have unrelated WIP).\u0026#xA;- Commit exactly once when green; conventional-commit subject ending with `[\u0026lt;bead-id\u0026gt;]`. Stop after the commit.\u0026#xA;- Do not modify files outside the bead\u0026#39;s scope.\u0026#xA;- If you cannot finish, write `.ddx/executions/20260506T103812-a69e960f/no_changes_rationale.txt` (what is done, what blocks, what a follow-up needs) before exiting. No commit and no rationale ⇒ DDx records `no_evidence_produced`. A well-justified no_changes beats a bad commit.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## no_changes contract\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;If you write `.ddx/executions/20260506T103812-a69e960f/no_changes_rationale.txt`, it MUST carry one of:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- `verification_command: \u0026lt;one-line shell command\u0026gt;` — the loop runs it (cwd = project root, 60s); exit 0 closes the bead, non-zero rejects.\u0026#xA;- `status: needs_investigation` + `reason: \u0026lt;why\u0026gt;` — bead stays open for triage.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;Bare rationales (\u0026#34;nothing to do\u0026#34;) are rejected.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Reports\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;Freestanding artifacts (investigation reports, findings docs) go under `.ddx/executions/20260506T103812-a69e960f/` (the per-attempt evidence directory under `.ddx/executions/`). **Never write reports to `/tmp` or any path outside the repository** — out-of-repo paths are invisible to the post-merge reviewer and cause BLOCK on missing evidence. If the bead names a specific in-repo path, use it; else default to `.ddx/executions/20260506T103812-a69e960f/\u0026lt;short-name\u0026gt;.md`. Stage and commit the report alongside code.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Bead overrides project defaults\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;The bead description and AC override CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, and conservative project defaults (YAGNI, DOWITYTD, no-docs-unless-asked) in this worktree — write whatever the bead asks for.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Review gate\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- The review is a gate, not an escape hatch — meet every AC in this pass.\u0026#xA;- Address every BLOCKING `\u0026lt;review-findings\u0026gt;` item; do not declare `no_changes` with blocking findings open.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Constraints\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- Work only inside this execution worktree.\u0026#xA;- Keep `.ddx/executions/` intact — DDx uses it as execution evidence.\u0026#xA;- **Never run `ddx init`** — the workspace is initialized; running it corrupts the bead queue.\u0026#xA;- Do not modify files outside the bead\u0026#39;s named scope.\u0026#xA;- Do not rewrite CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, or other project-instructions files unless the bead asks.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## When the work is done\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;After the commit succeeds and every AC is verified, stop. Return control to the orchestrator — do not keep exploring or testing.\n  \u003c/instructions\u003e\n  \u003cbead id=\"ddx-317d0254\"\u003e\n    \u003ctitle\u003eAdd default prose rules and DDx vocabulary\u003c/title\u003e\n    \u003cdescription\u003e\nCONTEXT\u0026#xA;DDx needs deterministic default prose rules and vocabulary so the CLI can flag common AI-writing tropes without relying on subjective model judgment. The rules must be tuned for DDx technical documents and configurable by projects.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;IN-SCOPE FILES\u0026#xA;- Default prose rule/vocabulary assets under the path selected by TD-036\u0026#xA;- Config schema/defaults for prose settings if TD-036 places them in this slice\u0026#xA;- cli/internal/docprose tests that evaluate rules against the fixtures from the fixture bead\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;RULE REQUIREMENTS\u0026#xA;- Detect unsupported generic praise and vague claims such as robust, seamless, comprehensive, industry-leading-style phrases when not backed by specifics.\u0026#xA;- Detect repeated formulaic openings or filler transitions where practical.\u0026#xA;- Support project vocabulary accept/reject lists.\u0026#xA;- Support at least technical and planning modes; public mode may share defaults if TD-036 says so.\u0026#xA;- Keep findings advisory metadata-ready: rule id, severity, rationale, suggested edit.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;OUT-OF-SCOPE\u0026#xA;- ddx doc prose command wiring.\u0026#xA;- Review integration.\u0026#xA;- Any AI-authorship score.\n    \u003c/description\u003e\n    \u003cacceptance\u003e\n1. Default rules/vocabulary are present in the asset path chosen by TD-036 and include DDx terminology accepts plus unsupported filler rejects.\u0026#xA;2. Focused tests run the rules against the fixture/golden cases and prove expected positives and negatives.\u0026#xA;3. Project vocabulary override behavior is covered by a test using accept and reject entries.\u0026#xA;4. No output includes an AI-authorship score or detector-bypass claim.\u0026#xA;5. `cd cli \u0026amp;\u0026amp; go test ./internal/docprose/...` passes.\u0026#xA;6. `lefthook run pre-commit` passes.\n    \u003c/acceptance\u003e\n    \u003clabels\u003ephase:2, area:cli, area:plugins, kind:feature, prose-quality\u003c/labels\u003e\n    \u003cmetadata parent=\"ddx-ccda7a32\" spec-id=\"TD-036\" base-rev=\"17439e752113d38348b8040b7b238aba1b44a045\" bundle=\".ddx/executions/20260506T103812-a69e960f\"/\u003e\n  \u003c/bead\u003e\n  \u003cgoverning\u003e\n    \u003cref id=\"TD-036\" path=\"docs/helix/02-design/technical-designs/TD-036